      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must match COU operating envelope within documented tolerances.",
      "rationale": "In-vitro experiments conducted at 37°C with bovine blood at physiological hematocrit (40±2%). Flow rates and rotational speeds matched COU specifications. Temperature, viscosity, and density characterized and reported. Test conditions adequately represent COU operating envelope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative agreement metric (e.g., normalized RMS error) must be computed and reported for all primary QoIs; comparison must include uncertainty bounds from both simulation and experiment.",
      "rationale": "CFD predictions were compared against experimental RHI measurements at all five operating points. Predicted values fell within 15% of measured values in all cases. The assessment team noted that while point-wise agreement is qualitatively favorable, a formal quantitative agreement metric with combined simulation and experimental uncertainty bounds was not computed. Uncertainty quantification for the experimental measurements was limited to repeatability estimates only; systematic uncertainty sources in the hemolysis assay were not characterized. The output comparison therefore does not fully satisfy the level 2 requirement for a rigorous uncertainty-inclusive comparison framework. Achieved level assessed as 1.",
      "achievedLevelJustification": "Formal uncertainty-inclusive comparison metric not computed; experimental systematic uncertainty uncharacterized. Qualitative agreement observed but quantitative acceptance criterion not formally demonstrated."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs must directly correspond to clinical hemolysis endpoints used in device clearance.",
      "rationale": "Primary QoI is the relative hemolysis index (RHI), which directly maps to the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) metric used in FDA guidance for CPB device evaluation. Secondary QoIs include shear stress distribution and exposure time, which are mechanistically linked to red blood cell damage. QoI relevance well-established in literature and consistent with predicate device comparison framework."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
